            <p>Jewish Publication Society of America.<lb/></p>
            <p>NEW YORK&#44; Dec. 13&#44; 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>REV. AND DEAR SIR&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>Referring to the enclosed circular&#44; we beg to invoke your<lb/> personal effort in behalf of the objects therein set forth.  If<lb/> you will kindly exert your eloquence FROM THE PULPIT&#44; we feel<lb/> assured gratifying results will follow.<lb/></p>
            <p>No plea is necessary from our side to inspire or strengthen<lb/> your own conception of the high character of the work for the<lb/> intellectual advancement of our people.  We feel that you will<lb/> realize how great is the obligation devolving upon the more favored<lb/> to promote the dissemination of Jewish knowledge and culture amongst<lb/> our people.  In this country&#44; in particular&#44; where the material<lb/> struggle is so great&#44; the necessity of withdrawing the mind from the<lb/> engrossing cares of business and enlarging the sphere of thought<lb/> must be apparent to all who have at heart the betterment of the people.<lb/></p>
            <p>We rely upon your cordial co&#45;operation&#44; and should be pleased<lb/> to receive assurance of your sympathy.<lb/></p>
            <p>Very Truly&#44;<lb/>
                JACOB H. SCHIFF&#44;<lb/>
                Chairman N. Y. Committee.<lb/>
                BENJAMIN F. PEIXOTTO&#44; Secretary.<lb/>
                Rev. Dr. G. Gottheil<lb/>
                Rev. Dr. A. Kohut&#44;	N. Y.<lb/>
                Henry M. Leipziger&#44;	Committee.<lb/></p>
            <p>Emanuel Lehman&#44;<lb/>
                Jacob H. Fleisch&#44;<lb/>
                James H. Hoffman&#44;<lb/>
                Edwin R. A. Seligman&#44;	Special Committee.<lb/>
                Newman Cowen&#44;<lb/>
                Edward Lauterbach&#44;<lb/>
                Myer S. Isaacs&#44;<lb/>
                Adolph L. Sanger&#44;<lb/></p>
            </body>
